				<a href="https://forums.sufficientvelocity.com/threads/brocktons-celestial-forge-worm-jumpchain.70036/page-649#post-20555398" class="bbCodeBlock-sourceJump" rel="nofollow" data-xf-click="attribution" data-content-selector="#post-20555398">Sakuya's Butler said:</a>
			
		</div>
	
	<div class="bbCodeBlock-content">
		
		<div class="bbCodeBlock-expandContent js-expandContent ">
			TMK the Anti-Spiral doesn't exist in Worms' specific subset of dimensions within the multiverse. OTOH, Joe's one <u>dense</u> idiot, not seeing the forest for the trees, so yes, his mentality IS a problem.<br>
<br>
<i>Especially</i> as he's already been GIVEN the intimate knowledge, which he knows at a fundamental, soul-deep level, that acting like Kamina or Simon....<br>
<br>
<b>WORKS</b>.<br>
<br>
Its like...<br>
<br>
Someone being given the entire combine powerset of the Justice League AND the Avengers...<br>
<br>
Then ignoring the obvious bonuses they could leverage together, to instead tinker around as Tony Stark and only briefly using the superficial 'tip of the iceberg' level abilities, and not really getting into the meat of his powers.<br>
<br>
(Doesn't help either that he truly cannot blame lack of time, as he has, iirc, knowledge of how to create a DBZ Hyperbolic Time Chamber)<br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong, I like the story, I really do. I'm just waiting with relish the moment Joe realizes he fucked up horribly ages ago, prior to March EVER showing up, and even back then could have gone to the mat against Endbringers and won. All those deaths, maimings, misunderstandings, resources lost, enemies made, opportunities squandered...<br>
<br>
Because he wasn't truly thinking outside the box.<br>
<br>
I'm going to enjoy that moment.
		</div>
		<div class="bbCodeBlock-expandLink js-expandLink"><a role="button" tabindex="0">Click to expand...</a></div>

<div class="bbCodeBlock-shrinkLink"><a>Click to shrink...</a></div>
	</div>
</blockquote>Yes, Joe <i>could</i> fight the Endbringers right now. In fact, he could kill two of them.<br>
<br>
With <i>a hell of a lot</i> of collateral damage. Like sunken coastlines and an irradiated Australia. Yes, to us readers, that might sound like a worthwhile trade. One continent for the planet... but we don't have to live with the literal millions to billion+ lives that would cost. Joe doesn't have the technology to take out the Endbringers without massive collateral, not yet.<br>
<br>
And then there's the cost of killing one even <i>without</i> collateral. Namely, there's more of them, and they'll come armed with knowledge of Joe and how he killed the previous ones. And alerting Scion to a system threat. And drawing the Fallen to Brockton Bay like flies... and guess who the Fallen have that Joe <i>Isn't</i> immune to, who canonically visits Brockton Bay? Yes, Valefor. Picture a Joe controlled by Endbringer worshippers.<br>
<br>
And then there's the third Endbringer. Let's say Joe keeps things local, doesn't fight Endbringers but pulls out the big guns, uses the big name tech he has. The Simurgh would become aware of the threat he poses the moment that tech leaves the Workshop. He doesn't yet have anything that can throw off her precog well enough to protect himself. Next thing you know, she's either paying him a personal visit or sending Ziz bombs by the dozens.<br>
<br>
So no, Joe could not have fought the Endbringers and won prior to March showing up. In fact, his passenger explicitly told him it was a horrible idea. Joe has damn good reasons for waiting until he's protected from the Simurgh before bringing out his big guns, as Roustabout has repeatedly pointed out. Even then, it's been hinted that he won't go on a warpath against the Endbringers once able. Killing them isn't a good idea.</div>
				
			</div>

			
	
	
		
	

